n, which can reduce the amount of data processed in the joins.\n\n2. **JOIN_CONDITION_PUSH**: This rule will push predicates in a join into the inputs to the join, optimizing the join operation.\n\n3. **FILTER_SUB_QUERY_TO_CORRELATE**: This rule can help convert the subquery into a correlate, potentially improving the efficiency of the subquery execution.\n\n### Transformation Steps:\n1. **Apply FILTER_INTO_JOIN**: Push filter conditions such as `p_size = 7` and `p_type like \'%COPPER\'` into the join conditions to reduce the data processed in the joins.\n\n2. **Apply JOIN_CONDITION_PUSH**: Push join predicates into the inputs of the join to optimize the join operation.\n\n3. **Apply FILTER_SUB_QUERY_TO_CORRELATE**: Convert the subquery calculating the minimum `ps_supplycost` into a correlate to improve execution efficiency.\n\n### Optimized Query:\nAfter applying the selected rules, the query would be transformed to optimize the join and subquery execution. The exact SQL transformation would depend on the database optimizer\'s capabilities, but the conceptual transformation involves pushing filters and optimizing the subquery execution.\n\n```python\n[\n    "FILTER_INTO_JOIN",\n    "JOIN_CONDITION_PUSH",\n    "FILTER_SUB_QUERY_TO_CORRELATE"\n]\n```', 'time': 4.118568420410156}
